spanGrp.span: ‘Today at some point I saw something in something;
Jirda yís të mĩgalë (_) sũẽ-ra-mĩ jele jãrga
what I saw when I watched it was that first a man appeared with something white around his head.
Ji (_) í sũã'-je nẽ je rö nãmĩga sũã'-je-nẽ-ra s sögötöranã pekaga desãu tsagu paböt-lë wa rö surrunã
He was shaking something outside the house.
Je të jirö wökbe-gẽ-nẽ jũ shebega bi
Inside the house there was a girl sitting;
Ta jũ jãrga nẽ ra pebusi kajkiri nã
she had a child lying down on a nice bench they had made.
je wã í yaba jie-lë-wã-nẽ kalwak nã (_) yulei wã bá ramã jãrga
í wã yaba jie-lë-wã Yaba kapá-wã
She left him alone and went out with her husband.
jawatanã-ite eglauña (m) Ta jie jẽk yasã' jũ shebega í juape ra
Where they went I don’t know.
Mãga í mẽnẽu-lo ka juenẽ s-wö inga
They thought the child was asleep; so, they left him sleeping while they went for a walk, maybe.
Je í begetsá yaba kapá-wã jetanã-ite köpö mientras ke jie-wa mĩ-gẽu-lo-mĩ ñãyulö le
Meanwhile I see that two little pacas came to where the child was sleeping.
Je deleigara yís í sũẽ-ra komo kono bi yabla bi (_) deu-lo bo-l mãĩ yaba kablali köpö ska
I thought they were going to devour or frighten him,
begetsá yís í kete-gẽ-wã-ite le o mẽleche-gẽ-ite rö
But it was not like that.
but they woke him up and the child got up and they went before him, so chased them;
Í shki-wã-ka-ite yaba jẽk kagá Kepa í mẽnẽu-lo-ka ñalawötso ñalawötso töjiáu-mĩ-ite
They got to a huge place with lots of nice trees and flowers;
Í mẽnẽu-lo-ka kal sigenã köũ bá ramã Pe mamawö juer bá ramã
The child chased them and they were ahead.
Yaba të í töjiáu-mĩ töjiáu-mĩ jie-wa julur-gate ñalawötsoka
The child’s shirt got stuck on a tree; it tore apart;
Yaba paglö jienawatanã-nẽ kal bata mẽ Kashanãu-mĩ
he screamed at them, but they would not listen to him.
je ãr-gẽ-nẽ í tsagara ka í wakwa të í kuge
Next, there appeared a fucking snake;
Jekepa (_) (_) jeskanẽ mãga kaljula jãrga kebé chi tsõnã-te-nẽ (_)
it rolled over the child with its tail all the way up to his neck.
Je të yaba pabotrá-wã-nẽ í mẽlek wa butrá-wã-ite köũ degãu kuli ska (_)
The child opened its mouth, but I don’t believe that;
Yaba të í kö jakke-gẽ-nẽ ka s-wã je köganã
No child could ever open a snake’s mouth like that!
¡Jirö kebé (_) kö jakke yabla të je bi nã
How come it didn’t bite him, if he pulled out its tongue all the way?
¿Mẽnẽbi ka wã í kunẽnẽ nã Kö jakká-ite jekepa köktö yá-ite betsí (_)
There the snake got mad and threw the child down to the ground and he went up to another tree.
Jeskanẽra kebé ulunã' të yaba báu-mĩ-nẽ jiski inga (_) Jẽk pakká-sã'-nẽ kal kwãwã jãrga nẽ
There he lost sight of the ones who took him there [the pacas].
Jeska bö ñẽ mẽnẽu mẽnẽu-wã mẽnẽjar je shenã'ka-wã-nẽ í wö jãrga nẽ
So he stayed with the snake.
Then the place looked nice, with flowers, and other nice things in the middle.
tögapanẽra bá ramã pekã' juela mamawö köũ jirö jirö otro wa julur-gẽ-nẽ í sa/ shanãnẽ böi nẽ
Then it seems that the parents came back home;
je (m) tögapa í kaga-wa juela deu-lo-nẽ jũ ska nẽ
they got to the place where they had left the child asleep,
Kawãu-lo-nẽ mãĩ të yaba jatanã köpö ska ra
but the child was not sleeping there.
They got scared and went out with sticks, they searched for the child under the trees, the flowers, in the middle of the bush,
Í kaga-wa mẽletenã'-wã kawãu-lo-nẽ je-wa desãu-lo jũ shebega kal ra beteu-lo-te-nẽ kal digĩ jãrgatenẽ mamawö digĩ jãrgatenẽ kã'yega jãrgatenẽ (m)
but they could not find him.
Yaba yulö-nẽ ka ĩã yaba kõr ta
They made noise and then a wolf appeared before them;
Koyir-gate-nẽ mãga jeska se je të sũẽ-ra lobo bi nẽ desãu-nẽ í wömĩ nẽ (_)
they tried to scare it off; they thought it had devoured the child;
të mẽleche-gẽ-nẽ begetsá-ite je nẽ të yaba katá-wã rö (_)
they hit it with sticks, but it was not that one that had devoured the child.
Jebö begáte-ite köũ nẽ kal wa (_) ka í rö je kuna Ka je wã yaba katanẽ-wã kuna
The child had been taken away by something else; he was somewhere else.
Ta yaba mẽnẽtse rö kwãwã dul-nẽ rö kwãwãnẽ (_)
They did not know what to do or think or where to go;
Ta ultimo/ jeska í wakwa ka inga juenẽ mãga jirö mẽwẽ-ite mãga jirö begetse-ite mãga mẽnẽwã mĩu-lo
who could have taken the child away?
Something must have devoured the child, or he might be lost, or dead.
yaba katá-wã jirö të í rö Ta yaba shenã'-wã í rö yaba döá-wã
There something else appeared that we call bear. It was big and black;
jeska mãga otro tsõnãte-nẽ rö komo se í she-ra rö oso bi keyege nẽ dolonã nẽ
it was holding the child in its hand; it was playing with the child in the middle of the flowers.
Je nẽ të yaba gugácha-nẽ jula jãrga nẽ Je kajki-nẽ jinõ kwãwã nẽ yaba ra mamawö shajãrganẽ
It was kissing and tickling him.
Je jatanã'-te í wölakse-gẽ í kipabloe-gẽ ĩã
So they got very scared because the child was lost.
Jera jie-wa mẽletẽr-te tãĩ (_) Yaba shenã'-wã í rö
Who might have taken the child away?
There they were and there it ends.
(_) Jeska bi bö í wakwa dujali bi bö jeska bö í õnã'-wã
I don’t know what and where took him away;
Jeska s-inga juenẽ nã jirö mẽnẽu mãga í mẽnẽtse í wã rö
or whether they took care of him.
Jatanã' bi (m) jera je të í kunãnẽ-gẽ-nẽ bi (m)
Jebi bö í (m) kaga min mina-wa jatanã'-tanã je begetsö
Jeska jebi bö í õnã'-wã rö
And the place looked very nice.’
